---
import CalculatorLayout from "../../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro";
import { CdnCostPlanner } from "../../components/calculators/CdnCostPlanner";

const title = "CDN Cost Calculator: Bandwidth, Requests, Origin Egress, and Peak-Month Planning";
const description =
  "Plan CDN cost across bandwidth, request fees, and origin egress in one model. Built for image-heavy storefront, video or download delivery, dynamic API edge traffic, and launch-month cache-miss scenarios.";
---
<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/calculators/cdn-cost-calculator"
  intro="Use the full CDN planner when one number is not enough. This page keeps edge bandwidth, request fees, and origin egress visible together so you can see which cost surface really dominates the month."
  examples={[
    "Image-heavy storefront: bandwidth is often the largest cost surface, but campaign peaks can still shift the request and origin share.",
    "Dynamic API at the edge: request share and origin egress share can overtake bandwidth even when delivered GB looks modest.",
    "Launch month with lower cache hit rate: a peak window can raise all three surfaces together, especially origin exposure.",
  ]}
  includes={[
    "One planner for bandwidth share, request share, and origin egress share.",
    "Scenario presets for storefront, video or download delivery, dynamic API edge traffic, and launch-month cache misses.",
    "Peak-month comparison and next-action guidance after the estimate.",
  ]}
  excludes={[
    "Provider-specific rate cards or contract negotiation details.",
    "Adjacent CDN add-ons such as WAF, logs, and image processing fees unless you add them separately.",
  ]}
  how={[
    "Modeled total = edge bandwidth cost + request-fee cost + estimated origin egress exposure.",
    "Bandwidth share vs request share tells you whether bytes or request units dominate the edge bill.",
    "Origin egress share shows how much cache misses or refill overhead still leak cost back to the origin.",
    "Peak-month modeling keeps launch or incident traffic from disappearing into one average month.",
  ]}
  faqs={[
    {
      q: "When should I use the full planner instead of narrow calculators?",
      a: "Use this page when you need to compare bandwidth, request fees, and origin egress together. Use narrow calculators when you already know which one line item moved first.",
    },
    {
      q: "Which number moved first on the CDN bill?",
      a: "If viewer delivery jumped, start with bandwidth. If bots or small-object traffic jumped, request fees may have moved first. If cache hit rate fell, origin egress is usually the next number to inspect.",
    },
    {
      q: "What scenarios does this page model best?",
      a: "Image-heavy storefront, video or download delivery, dynamic API at the edge, and launch-month traffic with lower cache hit rate.",
    },
    {
      q: "What should I validate before using the output in planning?",
      a: "Confirm edge GB, request units, cache hit rate, and origin pricing against billing, analytics, or a written traffic assumption set. Then compare baseline and peak separately.",
    },
  ]}
  lastUpdated="2026-06-19"
  related={[
    { href: "/guides/cdn-costs", label: "Guide: CDN cost diagnosis" },
    { href: "/calculators/cdn-bandwidth-cost-calculator", label: "Edge bandwidth calculator" },
    { href: "/calculators/cdn-request-cost-calculator", label: "Request-fee calculator" },
    { href: "/calculators/cdn-origin-egress-calculator", label: "Origin leakage calculator" },
    { href: "/guides/origin-egress-vs-cdn-bandwidth", label: "Origin vs edge guide" },
    { href: "/guides/cdn-cost-comparison", label: "Provider comparison guide" },
  ]}
>
  <div class="prose">
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:0">
      Start here when the real question is not "what is the CDN rate?" but "which cost surface dominates this month
      once bandwidth, request fees, and origin exposure all stay visible together?"
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Which number moved first?</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bandwidth moved</strong> when viewer-facing edge delivery or regional mix is the main issue.</li>
      <li><strong>Request fees moved</strong> when small assets, bots, or cache-key sprawl inflate billable requests.</li>
      <li><strong>Origin egress moved</strong> when lower cache hit rate or refill overhead leaves the origin paying more than expected.</li>
      <li><strong>Use this page</strong> when you need to keep all three surfaces visible before deciding where to optimize.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Scenario menu for real CDN planning</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Image-heavy storefront</strong>: asset weight and merchandising peaks shape the month.</li>
      <li><strong>Video or download distribution</strong>: delivered GB dominates and peak release windows matter.</li>
      <li><strong>Dynamic API at the edge</strong>: request share and origin leakage can outrank bandwidth.</li>
      <li><strong>Launch month with lower cache hit rate</strong>: all three cost surfaces can move together.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      The planner is strongest when you still need to compare <strong>bandwidth share</strong>, <strong>request
      share</strong>, and <strong>origin egress share</strong> before deciding whether the next move is optimization,
      provider comparison, or deeper single-surface math.
    </p>
  </div>

  <CdnCostPlanner client:load />

  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">When to start here instead of a narrow calculator</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Start here when you do not yet know whether bandwidth share, request share, or origin egress share is the dominant cost surface.</li>
      <li>Start with the narrow calculators when one line item is already clearly isolated and you only need deeper math on that slice.</li>
      <li>Keep this page tool-first: use it to compare surfaces, then route to the narrower calculator or guide for the next decision.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">What this planner still misses</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>WAF, bot mitigation, edge functions, logs, and image-optimization add-ons.</li>
      <li>Contracted discounts or provider-specific tier tables that require a vendor-specific worksheet.</li>
      <li>Operational changes that affect cache hit rate abruptly, such as invalidation storms or launch-day cache churn.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Next step by intent</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      Use the cards below to leave this page on purpose. If one surface clearly dominates, move to the narrower math.
      If the total still feels fuzzy, go back to diagnosis rather than forcing a blended answer.
    </p>
    <div class="grid">
      <a class="card2 tool col-6" href="/calculators/cdn-bandwidth-cost-calculator/">
        <div class="tool-title">Bandwidth is clearly dominant</div>
        <div class="tool-desc">Go deeper on delivered edge GB, effective $/GB, and peak delivery windows.</div>
      </a>
      <a class="card2 tool col-6" href="/calculators/cdn-request-cost-calculator/">
        <div class="tool-title">Request fees are clearly dominant</div>
        <div class="tool-desc">Go deeper on request-unit math, bots, cache-key sprawl, and request-class assumptions.</div>
      </a>
      <a class="card2 tool col-6" href="/calculators/cdn-origin-egress-calculator/">
        <div class="tool-title">Origin egress is the next risk</div>
        <div class="tool-desc">Go deeper on cache-hit decay, refill overhead, and how much traffic the origin still serves.</div>
      </a>
      <a class="card2 tool col-6" href="/guides/cdn-costs/">
        <div class="tool-title">Need diagnosis before more math</div>
        <div class="tool-desc">Use the guide when you still need to define the bill boundary and decide what belongs in the model.</div>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</CalculatorLayout>
